{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2011}} {{Use Australian English|date=August 2011}} {{Infobox AFL biography | name = Alan Cransberg | image = | fullname = Alan John Cransberg | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1958|09|22|df=y}} | birth_place = [[Bunbury, Western Australia|Bunbury]], [[Western Australia]] | death_date = | death_place = | originalteam = [[South Bunbury Football Club|South Bunbury]] | height = | weight = | position = | statsend = 1983 | years1 = 1976–83 | club1 = [[Swan Districts]] | games_goals1 = 115 (33) | careerhighlights = * [[Swan Districts]] premiership side 1982, 1983 }}
'''Alan John Cransberg''' (born 22 September 1958) is an [[Australia]]n businessman and former [[Australian rules footballer]] who is the current chairman of the [[West Coast Eagles]] in the [[Australian Football League]], as well as a member of the boards of several other organisations. Cransberg grew up in [[Bunbury, Western Australia|Bunbury]], [[Western Australia]], attending [[Bunbury Senior High School]]. He played for the [[South Bunbury Football Club]] in the [[South West Football League]] (SWFL), before being recruited by the [[Swan Districts Football Club]] in the [[Perth]]-based [[West Australian Football League|Western Australian National Football League]] (WANFL) prior to the 1976 season. Cransberg went on to play 115 games for Swan Districts, mainly playing as a [[Backline (football)|defender]]. He played at [[centre half-back]] in Swan Districts' 1982 premiership team, and also played in the premiership side the following season, retiring after the 1983 season to concentrate on his business career.<ref name="alcoa">[http://www.alcoa.com/australia/en/pdf/Cransberg_Alan_bio.pdf Alan Cransberg biography] – Alcoa Australia. Retrieved 15 August 2011.</ref> Cransberg graduated from the [[University of Western Australia]] in 1980 with an [[honours degree]] in [[civil engineering]].<ref name="bio">[http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/people/person.asp?personId=11764132&ticker=AA:US&previousCapId=702422&previousTitle=Alcoa%20of%20Australia%20Limited Alan Cransberg: executive profile and biography] – Business Week. Retrieved 15 August 2011.</ref> He joined [[Alcoa Australia]] after his graduation, and held various planning, engineering and managerial positions from 1981 to 1997, before being appointed location manager of the company's [[Pinjarra, Western Australia|Pinjarra]] alumina refinery in 1998.<ref name="bio"/>
In 2001, Cransberg moved to [[Texas]] to become location manager of the [[Point Comfort]] alumina refinery and chemicals complex, and, in 2003, he was made President, Primary Metals United States Division, with his title expanded in 2004 to President, Primary Metals North America Division. From 2004, he was President, Global Manufacturing for Alcoa's Global Primary Products group, based in [[New York City]], and later served as chairman of Alcoa's Employee Relations Council.<ref name="bio"/> Cransberg was made a vice-president of Alcoa in 2006.<ref name="wce1">[http://www.westcoasteagles.com.au/tabid/7155/default.aspx?newsid=57377 Cransberg on board] – westcoasteagles.com.au. Published 4 April 2008. Retrieved 15 August 2011.</ref> Returning to Australia in 2008, he was promoted to the position of managing director of [[Alcoa Australia]]. In this role, he [[Australia 2020 Summit participants|participated]] in the [[Australia 2020 Summit]] as part of the "Productivity Agenda" group.<ref>[http://www.australia2020.gov.au/docs/2020_participants_alphabetical.pdf Alphabetical list of participants] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120724060654/http://www.australia2020.gov.au/docs/2020_participants_alphabetical.pdf |date=24 July 2012 }} – Australia 2020 Summit. Retrieved 15 August 2011.</ref> He joined the [[West Coast Eagles]]' board in 2008,<ref name="wce1"/> and was appointed chairman for the [[2011 West Coast season|2011 season]], taking over from [[Mark Barnaba]].<ref>[http://www.perthnow.com.au/business/wa-company-news/west-coast-eagles-appoint-new-chairman-alan-cransberg/story-e6frg2s3-1225890708249 West Coast Eagles appoint new chairman, Alan Cransberg] – [[PerthNow]] Business New. Published 12 July 2010. Retrieved 15 August 2011.</ref> Cransberg currently also holds board positions with the [[Australian Institute of Management]] (AIM), the [[Chamber of Commerce and Industry of Western Australia]] and the [[Black Swan State Theatre Company]], and is also involved with the [[Australia Business Arts Foundation]] (ABAF) in a counselling position.<ref name="alcoa"/> He currently lives in [[Mandurah]], and has four children (Matt, Josie, Jamie, and Sasha) with his wife, Jenny.<ref>[http://www.alcoa.com/global/en/careers/pdf/AWN_Work_Life_Blend_Guide.pdf Work/Life Blend Guide] – Alcoa Women's Network. Published July 2005. Retrieved 15 August 2011.</ref> Cransberg's brother, [[Peter Cransberg]], was also a footballer, and played for {{WAFL EP}} and {{AFL Ess}}.<ref name="alcoa"/>
